Introduction and Explanatory Data Analysis

Throughout recent past years, the popularity of the makeup industry has skyrocketed. This most likely occurred with the rise of social media and social media personalities from YouTube, Instagram, and even TikTok. While this might seem great, one side that is often ignored is the exclusivity that comes with the makeup industry. In fact, many people with darker complexions have an extremely difficult time finding their perfect foundation shade, and this is a huge disservice to communities of color.

We took this into consideration and explored the makeup_shades dataset from Data.World and their article Diversity of Makeup Shades. The sampled populations were best seller beauty brands in four different countries - U.S., Nigeria, India, and Japan. After consultating different lists produced from sources such as Amazon, Popsugar Beauty, Refinery29, Beauty In Lagos, and other sources, a list of brands were compiled. To find the shade color, each brands website was visited in May of 2018, with the color and price being recorded based on the liquid foundation line that had the largest variety of shades. Adobe Photoshop was used to determine the lightness value.

When glimpsing the data, we noticed about ~100 nas under best_seller. To make our analysis easier, we filtered out nas from the data set. We were curious to see if there could be any relationship between the specific lightness and price (i.e.are darker shades more expensive?) as well as if this differs by country, because we believe that price is an important factor in determining the likelihood of someone purchasing a product.

The question we wanted to answer was: Is there a relationship between price and lightness across different value makeup brands around the world? We chose the variables price (quantitative response variable) and lightness(explanatory variable), organized by the categorical variable best_seller because it allowed us to see shade variability separated into four countries. This allowed us to observe the diversity of each countrys products and shades, as well as if there is any correlation with price in US dollars.

Linear Regressions

Hypothesis Test

For our linear regression models, we explored whether or not there was a difference in price of makeup best_sellers across different countries. Our null hypothesis is that there is no difference in price, while our alternative hypothesis is that there is a difference in price.

Figure 5b Parallel slopes model graph with white background to better view data points

For our parallel slopes model, the baseline, India, was represented by the equation: price_hat_India = 9.1686 -0.007326x, in which x equals the lightness variable. For every 1 unit increase in lightness, we expect to see, on average, an decrease of price by approximately $0.007 (the slope), and when the lightness is equal to zero (the intercept and lightest possible shade) we expect the price to be, on average, $9.20.

Besides from our baseline, we also investigated data for makeup bestsellers in Japan. This was represented by the equation: price_hat_Japan = (9.2 + 36.72) -0.007326x. As we can see, the slope stays constant for all lines, so we can expect to see that for every unit increase in lightness, there is also a decrease in price by approximately $0.007 on average. When the lightness is equal to zero, we expect to see the price to be, on average, $(9.2 + 36.72), or $45.92, so in spite of this constant slope, Japan starts off at a much higher price. This leads us to believe that from the start, the cost of makeup best sellers in Japan is much more expensive than the cost in India.

Nigeria, on the other hand, does not appear to show behavior as drastic as Japan. The regression line for Nigeria is represented by price_hat_Nigeria = (9.2 + 7.88) -0.007326x, where for every one unit increase in lightness, we expect the price to decrease by $0.007 on average. We also expect the price to be (9.2 + 7.88), or $17.08 on average, when the lightness is equal to zero. While this price might not be as expensive as the price in Japan, it is still higher than India because we add $7.88 to Indias intercept ($9.20).

Lastly, we analyzed at the data for makeup bestsellers in the U.S. The regression line for the U.S. is represented by the equation price_hat_US = (9.2 + 15.57) -0.007326x. We expect the price to decrease, on average, by $0.007 for every one unit increase in lightness, and when the lightness is equal to zero, the price is expected to be $(9.2 + 15.57) or $24.77 on average. Compared to India, we expect for the price of makeup best sellers in the U.S. to be $15.57 more expensive.

From this model, when the lightness is equal to zero, we can see that the price of makeup best sellers in India is the cheapest at $9.20, compared to the other countries which have much higher prices. Japan being the most expensive at $45.92, then the U.S. at $24.77, and finally Nigeria at $17.08. We can see that there is a negative correlation between price and lightness in all countries (India, Japan, Nigeria, the U.S.) as a result of having a negative slope.

Figure 6 Interaction model linearity plot comparing lightness (x-axis) to price in dollars (y-axis). India is acting as the baseline (main slope of comparison). Plot compares price and lightness of foundations across four different countries. We did not choose this model.

At first glance, our interaction model may look similar to our parallel slopes model, but they are actually different. See Appendix for further explanation.

The interaction model is not ideal compared to the parallel slopes model, and the reasoning behind this lies in the p-values. In the summary table, each row represents a hypothesis test, and the column furthest to the right shows a p-value for each test that was obtained. We usually use a significance level of 0.05 in order to determine whether the result is significant or not. P-values less than 0.05 imply that there is significance (we can reject the null hypothesis because there is evidence in favor in the alternative hypothesis), and those greater than 0.05 do not have significance (we fail to reject the null). As we can see from the summary table for the parallel slopes model, weve obtained p-values all greater than the significance level for seven out of the eight rows (0.7366, 0.7098, and 0.9995, just to name a few). This means that it is not significant to have several different slopes for our model. In other words, no evidence was provided against the null hypothesis. On the other hand, our parallel slopes model does exhibit extremely small p-values for four out of five of the rows (examples include 0.02, 0.0026, and 3.79e-14). This tells us that there is significance in having different intercepts, which is why our parallel slopes model is more ideal, meaning there was evidence in favor of the alternative hypotheses. Here the alternative hypotheses are each different country has its own intercept and the price at lightness equal to zero should be different for each country.

Limitations Plots

Constant Variance Plot

ggplot(data = makeup_model, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") +
   theme_minimal(base_size=20)+
  xlab("Fitted values") +
  ylab("Residuals")

Figure 7a Residuals versus fitted values plot. Dotted line represents where residuals are equal 0.

Our constant variance plot is not ideal. The fitted values represent the price we expect to see from our linear model using the makeups lightness while the residuals represent the observed price minus the expected price. Each point is the expected price from our model and how close it was to the original price in the data. An ideal plot would have residual values within a certain range throughout all fitted values. We would be able to draw a rectangle encompassing all the points to show that across all levels of our expected prices, our residuals stay within a certain range and has constant variance. Ideally, the plot would demonstrate as our expected prices from our model increase, we would expect similar differences in our residuals.

However, from our plot, it is clear that a box would not we suit the points. The points instead fit a more triangular shape with a smaller range of residual values (from -7 to 5) at smaller fitted values around an expected price of 10 and gradually expand to the largest range (-27 to 23) at larger fitted values around an expected price of 45. Thus, our constant variance plot demonstrates that as our expected prices from our model increase, we also expect greater differences in our residuals. Our model does not demonstrate constant variance.

Quantile-quantile plot

qqplot <- lm(price ~ lightness, data = makeup_shades)
ggplot(data = question1a, aes(sample = .resid)) +
  geom_qq() +
  xlab("Theoretical Quantiles") + # curves line up with the two peaks in the histogram
  ylab("Sample Quantiles") +
   theme_minimal(base_size=20)

Figure 7c Qq-plot of the residuals

The residuals histogram and qq-plot can be used to determine if the residuals are normally distributed. From on this histogram, the residuals appear to be right skewed, meaning that the residuals are not normally distributed. In fact, the histogram seems bimodal with one peak at residuals approximately equal to -12 and another when residuals are approximately 20. The qq-plot demonstrates this behavior as well with two places in the plot where the points curve away from a theoretical straight line that we could draw on this plot through the points. The gap in residuals from approximately 26 to 35 on the histogram is the break in the qq-plot at theoretical quantiles at approximately 1.6. Ideally, a qq-plot lies on a straight line to show that residuals are perfectly normal, which is not what our plot demonstrates. This means that we cannot assume we have normally distributed residuals or trust the p-values on the summary table.

Limitations and Conclusion

The question we set out to answer was whether there is a relationship between price and lightness across different value makeup brands around the world. We found no evidence that lightness is associated with price. Although this was not the original question we sought to answer, there is evidence that different countries have different prices in U.S. dollars for makeup because the p values on our models summary table for each individual countries intercept was much less than the statistical significant value 0.05. If we wanted to continue with this research, we may want to look at the data for makeup prices in more countries to see if makeup prices differ based on shade in different countries.

Our model did not fit well to the assumption metrics used to determine whether or model accurately represents the data. For linearity, each line in our parallel slopes model losely fits the points because many of the points followed alongside the line, but was either had prices extremely higher than the price for the line or lower than that price. Additionally, our model did not have nearly normal residuals or demonstrate constant variance. What cant we trust as much: p-values, area under the curve, so can we really trust the model we chose based on the p-values, assuming each makeup is independent.

Also, there were many limitations in this data set. The data set included many brands that have na for best_seller value , and we filtered all of those brands out of our data. Because we filtered out these brands, it may not be appropriate to generalize these results to all brands or even all countries because there were only 4 countries that were best sellers in the data set. Makeup prices may not vary greatly as lightness increases in a country in our data set, but in another country not represented by our data, it still could vary greatly. Similarly, a makeup brand in our data may not accurately show how prices for different shades of lightness vary in a different brand.

Appendix

Further explanations for the Interaction Model:

For our interaction model, the baseline, India, was represented by the equation: price_hat_India = 4.1129345 + 0.0607310x, in which x equals the lightness variable. For every 1 unit increase in lightness, we expect to see, on average, an increase of price by $0.06 (the slope), and when the lightness is equal to zero (the intercept and lightest possible shade) we expect the price to be, on average, $4.11. Because this is the interaction model, we can expect our intercepts and slopes to change, depending on the country we are looking at.

Besides from our baseline, we also looked at data for makeup bestsellers in Japan. This was represented by the equation: price_hat_Japan = (4.11 + 36.55) + (0.0607310 - 0.0001561)x. On average, we can expect to see that for every unit increase in lightness, there is an increase in price by $(0.0607310 - 0.0001561), or approximately $0.06. When the lightness is equal to zero, we expect to see the price to be, on average, $(4.11 + 36.55), or $40.66. Even though the slope of the baseline and the slope of price_hat_Japan are very similar, Japan is already at a much higher price.

Nigeria on the other hand does not appear to show behavior as extreme as Japan. The regression line for Nigeria is represented by price_hat_Nigeria = (4.11 + 12.64) + (0.0607310 - 0.0626467)x, where for every one unit increase in lightness, we expect the price to decrease by $(0.0607310 - 0.0626467), or $0.0019 on average. The slope of price_hat_Nigeria is roughly the same as the baseline, since that value isnt even equal to one cent. When the lightness is equal to zero, we expect the price to be (4.11 + 12.64), or $16.75 on average. While this price might not be as expensive as the price in Japan, it is still higher than the baseline.

Lastly, we looked at the data for makeup bestsellers in the U.S. The regression line for the U.S. is represented by price_hat_US = (4.11 + 21.73) + (0.0607310 - 0.0851736)x. We expect the price to decrease, on average, by $(0.0607310 - 0.0851736) or approximately $0.03 for every one unit increase in lightness. When the lightness is equal to zero, the price is expected to be $(4.11 + 21.73) or $25.84 on average. Compared to the baseline, the price of makeup best sellers in the U.S. are still more expensive to those in India.

In general, we can see that the price of makeup best sellers in India is the cheapest at $4.11, compared to the other countries which have much higher prices. Japan being the most expensive at $40.66, then the U.S. at $25.84, and finally Nigeria at $16.75. From the slopes, we can see that in Japan and India, there is a positive correlation between price and lightness, and then in Nigeria and the U.S., a negative correlation between the two.
